<BR><DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c6"><SPAN CLASS="c7">An unjustifiable shooting</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c6"><SPAN CLASS="c8">SECTION: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">EDITORIAL COPY; Pg. A16</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c6"><SPAN CLASS="c8">LENGTH: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">130 words</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c9"><SPAN CLASS="c2">Regarding the Aug. 12 front-page article &quot;FBI will investigate shooting in Mo.&quot;:</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c9"><SPAN CLASS="c2">Hatred of and violence toward minorities by some white law enforcement officials is still rife in 21st-century America, and it is no small wonder that black men fear and loathe white police officers. Even if </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c4">Michael Brown</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2"> provoked the officer, whose race has not been identified, by verbally abusing or striking him, there was no excuse for the use of deadly force against an unarmed person. The FBI will surely sort out what happened in Ferguson, Mo., and I trust the officer will be appropriately disciplined. No matter the outcome, nothing will bring </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c4">Michael Brown</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2"> back, and Ferguson now becomes the focal point for the future of race relations across the United States. </SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c9"><SPAN CLASS="c2"> Henry A. Lowenstein , New York</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c6"><SPAN CLASS="c8">LOAD-DATE: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">August 15, 2014</SPAN></P>
